        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Augusta Ga.</placeName>
                <date>28<hi rend="sup">th</hi>. Novr. 5626</date>.</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Revd. I. Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Yours of the <date>20<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> reached me<lb/>
                yesterday. I mentioned in my last that the current<lb/> Nos. of the Occident which I
                had ordered, had come<lb/> to hand. I have obtained another subscriber.<lb/>
                <persName>Mr L. Loeser</persName> of this city, in whom please mail<lb/> the
                Magazine. As soon as one or two Nos. reach<lb/> the parties, I will make the
                necessary collection. You<lb/> wish as in the extension of circulation in the
                country<lb/> parts shall receive due attention; and as I sometimes<lb/> travel to
                and for as <add>אוהל</add> and <add>במ"ק</add>, I will take <del>?</del><lb/>
                advantage of such occasions to advance its interests.<lb/> Be assured of my sincere
                willingness to do what I can<lb/> for you, and in this annexion<add>?</add> let me
                add, that my<lb/> advocacy of the Occident is unfettered as I have<lb/> undertaken
                the agency of no other paper or periodical.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have checked the incipient<lb/> Reform tendency, which made itself
                apparent in the<lb/> semi-official request of the Board of Trustees to use</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>the (Sunday School) Melodeon together with some of<lb/> the <placeName>Hazel
                    St.</placeName> Syngue hymns on <date>Thanksgiving Day</date>. I<lb/> refused
                    instante<add>?</add>, &amp; have probably given cause for some<lb/> ill will in
                consequence; but this is nothing new, as I<lb/> was <sic>martyrized</sic> by
                    <persName>Col <sic>Jacobs's</sic></persName> clique in
                    <placeName>Charleston</placeName><lb/> for my <del>pass</del> opposition to
                their wiles and intrigues<lb/> when they tried to use me for their purposes.
                They<lb/> never forgave my non-endorsation of <persName>Mr. Harris</persName>.
                It<lb/> was attempted to argue here the perfect legality of<lb/> playing on a
                musical instrument on a day that was<lb/> neither <date>Sabbath</date> nor Festival,
                but this I would not<lb/> discuss, as to my mind it was not the true point,<lb/> as
                I wished to guard against the entering wedge.<lb/> So whilst I remain here, and how
                long I may do<lb/> so is uncertain as the field dog not altogether<lb/> suit
                me,—“they hybrid” has received its quietus of<lb/> course; all this is entre
                nous.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Can you not brush up our people<lb/> in
                    <placeName>Jamaica</placeName>? My family letters from
                    <placeName>Kingston</placeName> depict<lb/> religion as in a state of decadence.
                The English &amp;<lb/> German Synagogue, will a model Congr—has an almost<lb/>
                nominal attendance on <add>שבת</add>, late and sparse, &amp;<lb/> on
                    <date>Sunday</date> evenings so hopeless is the attainment of</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p><add>מנין</add> that the Schule is not opened. Of the Portuguese<lb/> Congr I hear
                nothing; but <hi rend="underline">former</hi> advices lead me to<lb/> infer that
                that is little, if at all, better in this<lb/> respect. Alas! How are the mighty
                fallen! Our<lb/> friend <persName>M N Nathan</persName> should have taken the
                helm<lb/> again, for if aught could be done, he is the man<lb/> to do it.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr Jacobs</persName> reciprocates your kind<lb/>
                remembrance, and with much regard</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Believe me</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Yours truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">Henry S. Jacobs</persName>.</p>
        </body>
